  "doc_id": "23480",
  "text": "In this study, we investigated the use of the interspinous spacer on the kinematics of the lumbar spine. Pre-vious studies have reported that motion restricting surgical techniques, such as fusion, restrict the kinematics of a motion segment and can produce abnormal motion of the adjacent levels leading to instability. 14 -16 A biomechanical study of short lumbosacral fusions by Lee and Langrana showed a redistribution of mobility with the proximal level accommodating the extra deformation. [CITATION_1] Another study by Chow et al investigated the effects of anterior lumbar interbody fusion and found that the segment mobility of the adjacent segments was increased in both flexion and extension. [CITATION_2] Shono et al investigated the effects of posterior spinal instrumentation and found higher segmental displacement values at the cephalad motion segment in flexion-extension, lateral bending, and axial rotation. [CITATION_3] A possible consequence of implanting an interspinous spacer is that by restricting extension at one level, the kinematics of the adjacent levels may be altered, leading to degeneration and instability. We hypothesized that the implant will reduce the range of motion (ROM) of the treated level in flexion-extension while not affecting the treated level in axial rotation or lateral bending. We also hypothesized that the adjacent levels would not be affected.",
